Pandas Display Options

Tags: Pandas 08 Jun 2019

Import Pandas

These are Pandas settings after all…

import pandas as pd

First, let’s look at the default display options:

print("Maximum Number of Rows:", pd.options.display.max_rows)
print("Maximum Number of Columns:", pd.options.display.max_columns)
print("Maximum Number of Characters displayed in a Column:", pd.options.display.max_colwidth)

Not Enough Characters Displayed

This is a common challenge when working with text data or other medium to large strings like addresses, tweets, bios, summaries, etc. In column “1” you can see that each string longer than 50 characters has been truncated. Since most tweets are longer than 50 characters, we have used a tweet sentiment dataset to display this limitation.

How to Change Pandas Display Options - Hard Coded

Pandas display options are notebook-specific so they will be reset on new documents. To change them you will pass in two parameters to the pd.set_option() function: the option you would like to change and the new value. Here’s the syntax for my own future reference since I’m tired of googling it.

pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 999)
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', 100)
pd.set_option('display.max_colwidth', 200)

Setting Options Based on the Dataframe Shape

Using the dataframe shape attribute to control these settings can be helpful especially since most of your row viewing managment will usually come from the .head() function’s row parameter. Indlucing these rows in new notebooks after you have imported a dataframe will save you time.

pd.set_option('display.max_rows', AMES.shape[0])
pd.set_option('display.max_columns', AMES.shape[1])
